bors merge

I'd love to see more theory developed for these!

`Subtype.mk.injEq` isn't used.
```suggestion
    simp only [mk.injEq]
```

`Bool.coe_iff_coe` is a `simp` lemma, so you don't need to specify it. I suggest using either no `simp` lemmas as arguments of `simp`
```suggestion
    simpa using congr_fun₂ h v w
```
or all necessary ones with `only`
```suggestion
    simpa only [eq_iff_iff, Bool.coe_iff_coe] using congr_fun₂ h v w
```

I believe this may be redundant, as we already have `SimpleGraph.fromRel` which symmetrizes the relation and makes it irreflexive. For directed graphs, we can use `Digraph.mk` to construct the digraph induced by the given relation.

```suggestion
/-- The complete graph on a type `V` is the digraph with all pairs of vertices
adjacent. In `Mathlib`, this is usually referred to as `⊤`. Note that all vertices are adjacent to themselves. -/
def Digraph.completeGraph (V : Type u) : Digraph V where Adj := ⊤
```
Actually, `⊤` here isn't loopless.

You can use `tauto` for automated reasoning in propositional logic.
```suggestion
    top_le_sup_compl := fun G v w _ => by tauto
```

Note that `Nonempty V` is sufficient because even if there is only one vertex, we still have one loop in the complete graph. Also check this probably simpler approach:
```suggestion
instance [h : Nonempty V] : Nontrivial (Digraph V) := by
  use ⊥, ⊤
  obtain v := h
  apply_fun (·.Adj v v)
  simp
```
This bullet point doesn't convey much to me. You can't say "the relation" without the prior text giving some indication which relation!
Really "spanning" here? The empty digraph surely doesn't count as spanning.
It does because it's only empty in the sense of having no edges — it still has all the vertices `V`.

Oops, misled by the fact that spanning trees are connected by virtue of being trees, I was thinking that a spanning subgraph should be connected. 

Sorry for the noise!
I'd just remove this TODO. It's not actionable.
Is this the same as Quiver with a universe specialisation?

Yes, and it's not a class and not meant to be used as a class.

The main function of `Digraph` is to use graph theory terminology for a basic concept.
Possibly we could have a comment somewhere to this effect, but it's not essential.
Say digraph rather than graph in this doc string? And perhaps below.

It's not defeq to `Quiver` in Lean, right? Because it's a brand new structure.
I agree that it is equivalent in the `Equiv` sense.

How about "structurally equivalent"?

The comment about "not intended to be used as a class" is true, but it might give the wrong impression. The purpose of it not being a class is to be able to work with the whole lattice of digraphs on a given vertex type. Classes work best when there's the assumption that there's *the* digraph structure on the vertex type.

The more apt comparison by the way is to a plain relation. I'd start it out with something like "This module defines directed graphs on a vertex type `V`, which is simply the notion of a relation `V -> V -> Prop`. The intention is to develop the notion using the language of graph theory." Then in the next paragraph it could mention the relation to quivers.

This will also help graph theorists understand this module, since many have never heard of quivers before.
Can't you use `Fintype.ofSurjective` here to get this computabily?

Move this after `mk'` and then you can use it with `Fintype.ofBijective` (it saves needing that `Digraph V` have `DecidableEq`):
```lean
instance {V : Type*} [DecidableEq V] [Fintype V] : Fintype (Digraph V) :=
  Fintype.ofBijective Digraph.mk' <| by
    refine ⟨Embedding.injective _, ?_⟩
    classical
    intro G
    use fun v w ↦ G.Adj v w
    ext v w
    simp
```
Perhaps the docstring should mention that this is a spanning subgraph, not any subgraph

```suggestion
the intention here is to develop relations using the language of graph theory.
```

Seems weird to me that `sSup_adj` lemma (explicitly) takes `{a b : V}` while the others don't
```suggestion
theorem sSup_adj {s : Set (Digraph V)} : (sSup s).Adj a b ↔ ∃ G ∈ s, Adj G a b := Iff.rfl
```
Or adding the parameter to the other lemmas
